Checks to see if a string matches a specific rule.

Inputs\:
matchType - The type of match to perform.
toMatch - The string to check if matches another string.
matchTo - The string to match against.
ignoreCase - Boolean value for whether or not to ignore case during match.

Responses\:
success - The String matched.
failure - The string did not match, or something went wrong.

Runs multiple SSH command by creating an ssh shell and checking output against regular expressions

Inputs\:
host - hostname or ip address
port - the port number for running the command. It overwrites the port given inside the host input -in a syntax like host\:port-, if this exists.
command - the commands to execute. This should be made up of 'send ' and 'expect ' statements separated be newlines.
username - username to connect as
password - password
privateKeyFile - private key to be used during ssh authentication.
timeout - (optional, default 90 seconds) time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete
newlineCharacters - The character sequence to send as the enter key being pressed after each 'send' statement in a send expect script is processed. Either '\r\n' '\n' '\r' or a comma delimited list of ASCII escape sequences.
characterDelay - the delay in milliseconds between sending characters of the SSH commands. 

Responses\:
success - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
visualized - the output of the command in XML format
STDOUT - the STDOUT of the command

47b0ee5f-7441-4525-87ee-149b340f8b4d.9bf0286c-63a7-4b03-a648-42de210ab9d7.transition.description=Creates a shell enviroment variable names HPOO with value "yes" 47b0ee5f-7441-4525-87ee-149b340f8b4d.9ce09a2c-927f-4d80-a943-669b02593860.transition.description=Created a SSH Shell session 47b0ee5f-7441-4525-87ee-149b340f8b4d.c122d32d-086d-4091-9be0-6453859e5a41.prompt=Port Number\: 47b0ee5f-7441-4525-87ee-149b340f8b4d.description=
This sample flow shows two SSH Shell operations sharing the same SSH Shell Session.  SSH Shell Logon creates the SSH Shell Session to be shared.  The first SSH Shell operation creates a shell enviroment variable.  The second SSH Shell operation reads the enviroment variable.  To ensure the SSH Shell session is closed immediately, SSH Shell Logoff is in both the success and failure paths.

Inputs\:
host - Hostname or ip address.
port - The port number for running the command. It overwrites the port given inside the host input -in a syntax like host\:port-, if this exists.
username - Username to connect as.
password - Password of user. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.

Responses\:
success - No errors were encountered during flow execution.
failure - Something went wrong.  Errors were encountered while executing this flow.

Note\:
In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
